The paper deals with information theory and coding, specifically in the exponential regime. The abstract mentions lossy coding of a memoryless source and maximum likelihood decoding over a memoryless channel, which are both topics in information theory. The paper also discusses random-coding exponents for erasure and list decoding, which are common topics in coding theory. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory), followed by cs.ITP (Information Theory and Probability), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
